01:22.040 --> 01:25.900
When did you first get interested or become exposed to science fiction?

01:26.660 --> 01:29.540
Well, I'm afraid I wasted the first nine years of my life.

01:29.540 --> 01:39.100
In October 1926, I was passing by a newsstand and the issue of amazing stories for that month jumped right off the stand, grabbed hold of me, said,

01:39.320 --> 01:42.840
take me home little boy, you will love me and it will become a way of life.

01:44.340 --> 01:53.100
And in those early days, there was just the one magazine a month and it was like a man in a desert who sees an oasis.

01:53.100 --> 01:56.220
You know, you head for any drop of water you can find.

01:57.320 --> 02:04.000
I began combing the magazine markets, looking at the mundane periodicals in Liberty magazine.

02:04.360 --> 02:12.640
Occasionally, I found something new by H.G. Wells or Sax Romer with his Fumand Choo, super scientific villain.

02:12.640 --> 02:21.660
And in the pages of Argus, I discovered that this magazine, besides having westerns and romance and air war and whatnot,

02:21.860 --> 02:25.220
that they generally had some science fiction going.

02:25.480 --> 02:30.860
Some of the pioneer authors of Ray Cummings and R.F. Starsell and Victor Russo,

02:30.980 --> 02:37.440
there was a lot of Burroughs, Mars and Venus and Palucidar and those, and also in Blue Book Magazine.

02:37.440 --> 02:43.540
By 1930, we had about seven magazines.

02:43.920 --> 02:50.000
We had the amazing Quarterlies in addition to the Monthlies and Science Wonder had come along,

02:50.060 --> 02:53.360
which also had a Quarterly publication and Air Wonder.

02:53.800 --> 03:01.620
And there was astounding stories of super science started up, which is still going today under the modified title,

03:01.620 --> 03:09.520
Analog Science Fiction, and that original amazing from April 1926 is still being published and in my collection.

03:10.240 --> 03:20.220
By about 1929, rather mundane mother had begun to be somewhat worried about my collecting instinct.

03:20.520 --> 03:31.580
She encountered my magazine and said,

03:32.320 --> 03:38.260
Well, my dear mother lived till nearly 94 and was in my own home at the end of her life.

03:38.440 --> 03:44.440
Home was now four stories, 17 rooms, three garages in which you couldn't park a toothpick

03:44.440 --> 03:51.600
because we eliminated the cars from them and put in shelves and that is totaled with the science fiction collections.

03:51.720 --> 03:55.060
Matter of fact, whenever I see a garage sale nowadays, I buy another garage.

03:55.240 --> 03:59.580
I have two extra garages that are filling up around Los Angeles.

03:59.580 --> 04:05.300
So the collection has grown from that one single magazine back in October 1926.

04:05.300 --> 04:09.480
Here I am on the verge of my 55th anniversary in the field.

04:09.580 --> 04:21.020
Now there are 300,000 magazines and books and manuscripts and props from movies and artwork and stills.

04:21.280 --> 04:22.920
I stop at nothing.

04:23.100 --> 04:25.480
I even try to get space stamps from all over the world.

04:28.380 --> 04:34.320
It wouldn't be any stretch of the imagination to say that you have probably the most complete collection of science fiction anywhere.

04:34.760 --> 04:35.960
Well, that's what it is.

04:36.080 --> 04:38.300
I've been on both sides of the Iron Curtain.

04:38.480 --> 04:40.200
I've been upside down in Tasmania.

04:40.540 --> 04:42.620
I've been a thousand miles from the North Pole.

04:42.860 --> 04:47.860
I've been in Hungary and Czechoslovakia and East Germany.

04:48.220 --> 04:53.800
I've been to Japan and if there's any greater collection, it must be underground or well hidden.

04:53.800 --> 05:00.880
Naturally, I'm so intensely interested in the subject matter that I seek out collectors everywhere in the world.

05:01.660 --> 05:10.380
There are maybe half a dozen of us who have equal collections of magazines, as to say about 99% complete.

05:11.460 --> 05:16.020
There are certainly collectors with enormous numbers of books,

05:16.020 --> 05:23.520
but I go beyond that into autographs of the authors and the motion picture people.

05:23.720 --> 05:30.620
I go have Baylor Lugosi would sign Count Dracula and Frederick March, you've got an Academy Award for Jekyll and Hyde.

05:30.640 --> 05:39.060
He was signed for me both as Jekyll and as Hyde and I got Boris Karloff to sign as the Frankenstein monster and the mummy.

05:39.060 --> 05:52.060
And so, last 50 years I've wound up with 125,000 stills from all the fantastic movies ever made in the world.

05:52.280 --> 05:58.140
And 18,000 lobby cards and uncounted thousands of clippings.

05:58.840 --> 06:08.800
I get Hollywood Reporter and Variety and Publishers Weekly and I constantly cut out everything concerning science fiction and fantasy.

06:08.800 --> 06:09.780
And file it away.

